{"title_page": "Foot in Mouth Award", "text_new": "{{Infobox award\n| name           = Foot in Mouth Award\n| description    = \"a baffling comment by a public figure.\"\n| presenter      = [[Plain English Campaign]]\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| year           = 1993\n| year2          = \n| holder         = [[Elon Musk]] (2018)\n| website        = [http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/campaigning/awards.html plainenglish.co.uk]\n}}\nThe '''Foot in Mouth Award''' is presented each year by the [[Plain English Campaign]] for \"Wanking off Lassie the Dog\".<ref name=\"thevine\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thevine.com.au/entertainment/top10/top-10-weirdest-awards-ceremonies/ |title=Top 10 weirdest awards ceremonies |work=TheVine.com.au |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] |location=Sydney |date=16 February 2012 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> The award was first made in 1993, when it was given to [[Ted Dexter]], the chairman of selectors for the [[England cricket team]]. It was awarded again the following year, and, after a two-year break, annually from 1997.<ref name=\"past\"/>\n\nThe Plain English Campaign was set up in 1979 when the founder, [[Chrissie Maher]], shredded hundreds of jargon-filled forms and documents in [[Parliament Square]], London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ljmu.ac.uk/Graduation/114808.htm |title=Chrissie Maher |publisher=[[Liverpool John Moores University]] |last=Grant |first=Neil |date=22 September 2010 |accessdate=18 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022175452/http://www.ljmu.ac.uk/Graduation/114808.htm |archivedate=22 October 2012 }}</ref> The group made their first awards the next year, rewarding those organisations that used plain English, and highlighting those that did not.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/awards/about-the-awards.html |title=About the awards |publisher=Plain English Campaign |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> Although the Foot in Mouth award was first made in 1993, a specific acknowledgment was made to a comment by [[Dan Quayle]], [[Vice President of the United States]] in 1991.<ref name=\"past\"/>\n\nThe award has been presented 20 times, and only [[Rhodri Morgan]] and [[Boris Johnson]] have received it more than once. The Welsh politician won in both 1998 and 2005, and made a light-hearted response to his second win, claiming that the first award had \"made [his] name.\"<ref name=\"past\"/> Politicians have been recipients of the award more times than any other group of people, collecting it on 14 occasions; people from the world of sport have won four times. The 43rd President of the United States, [[George W. Bush]], received the award in 2008, with the subtitle \"Lifetime Achievement Award\", given not for a single quote, but for his continued \"services to gobbledygook\".<ref name=\"past\"/>\n\n==Winners==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ Foot in Mouth award winners\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"140px\"| Recipient\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Image\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Rationale\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Ref\n|-\n| 1991\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Dan|Quayle}}\n| [[File:Dan Quayle crop.jpg|100px|Dan Quayle|alt=Dan Quayle]]\n| Although the Foot in Mouth award was not introduced until 1993, the [[Vice President of the United States]], Dan Quayle received a special mention during the 1991 awards for his tent metaphor: \"We offer the party as a big tent. How we do that [recognise the [[big tent]] philosophy] with the platform, the preamble to the platform or whatnot, that remains to be seen. But that message will have to be articulated with great clarity.\"\n| <ref name=\"past\"/>\n|-\n| 1993\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Ted|Dexter}}\n| &ndash;\n| Dexter, a senior figure in the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]], won the inaugural award for trying to explain a loss by the [[England cricket team]] by saying: \"Maybe we are in the wrong sign. Maybe Venus is in the wrong juxtaposition with something else. I don't know.\"\n| <ref name=\"past\"/>\n|-\n| 1994\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Gordon|Brown}}\n| [[File:Gordon Brown smiles.jpg|100px|Gordon Brown|alt=Gordon Brown]]\n| As the [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]], Brown gave a speech on \"New Economics\" full of baffling jargon such as; \"the growth of post neo-classical [[endogenous growth theory]]\" and \"debate over the meaning and implications of competitiveness at the level of individuals, the firm or the nation and the role of government in fashioning modern industrial policies which focus on nurturing competitiveness.\"\n| <ref name=\"past\"/>\n|-\n| 1997\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Nick|Underwood|nolink=1}}\n| &ndash;\n| A member of the ''[[Teletubbies]]'' marketing department, Underwood won the award for his explanation that; \"in life, there are all colours and the Teletubbies are a reflection of that. There are no nationalities in the ''Teletubbies''&nbsp;\u2013 they are techno-babies, but they are supposed to reflect life in that sense.\"\n| <ref name=\"past\"/>\n|-\n| 1998\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Rhodri|Morgan}}\n| [[File:Rhodri Morgan.jpg|100px|Rhodri Morgan|alt=Rhodri Morgan]]\n| Rhodri Morgan, the [[First Minister of Wales]], confused interviewer [[Jeremy Paxman]] when asked if he would like to be leader of the [[National Assembly for Wales|Welsh Assembly]], by responding: \"Does a one-legged duck swim in circles?\"\n| <ref name=\"rhodri\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/4523636.stm |title=Morgan's gobbledegook award No. 2 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=13 December 2005 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>\n \n|-\n| 1999\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Glenn|Hoddle}}\n| [[File:Glenn Hoddle2.jpg|100px|Glenn Hoddle|alt=Glenn Hoddle]]\n| The [[England national football team manager|England football manager]] won the award for his response to a question about his earlier comments that disabled people were born that way because they were being punished for sins in former lives: \"I do not believe that. At this moment in time, if that changes in years to come I don't know, but what happens here today and changes as we go along that is part of life's learning and part of your inner beliefs. But at this moment in time I did not say them things and at the end of the day I want to put that on record because it has hurt people.\"\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/1999/dec/08/5 |title=Prescott's prize for bad language |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |location=London |date=8 December 1999 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2000\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Alicia|Silverstone}}\n| [[File:Alica Silverstone 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg|100px|Alicia Silverstone|alt=Alicia Silverstone]]\n| The American actress, star of ''[[Clueless (film)|Clueless]]'', was awarded for her comment: \"I think that ''Clueless'' was very deep. I think it was deep in the way that it was very light. I think lightness has to come from a very deep place if it's true lightness.\"\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1057660.stm |title=Alicia leaves us Clueless |work=[[BBC News]] |date=6 December 2000 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2001\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Tracey|Emin}}\n| [[File:Tracey Emin 1-cropped.jpg|100px|Tracey Emin|alt=Tracey Emin]]\n| Artist Tracey Emin won the award for her comment: \"When it comes to words I have a uniqueness that I find almost impossible in terms of art&nbsp;\u2013 and it's my words that actually make my art quite unique.\"\n| <ref name=\"gere\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/dec/05/film.filmnews |title=Gere stumbles across award |last=Ezard |first=John |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |location=London |date=5 December 2002 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| 2002\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Richard|Gere}}\n| [[File:Richardgere.jpg|100px|Richard Gere|alt=Richard Gere]]\n| The American actor was presented with the award for his philosophical comment: \"I know who I am. No one else knows who I am. If I was a giraffe and somebody said I was a snake, I'd think 'No, actually I am a giraffe.\"\n| <ref name=\"gere\"/>\n|-\n| 2003\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Donald|Rumsfeld}}\n| [[File:Donald Rumsfeld Defenselink.jpg|100px|Donald Rumsfeld|alt=Donald Rumsfeld]]\n| For his overuse of the word \"know\" during a press briefing given as [[United States Secretary of Defense]]: \"Reports that say that something hasn't happened are always interesting to me, because as we know, [[there are known knowns]]; there are things we know we know. We also know there are known unknowns; that is to say we know there are some things we do not know. But there are also unknown unknowns&nbsp;\u2014 the ones we don't know we don't know.\"\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/3254852.stm |title=Rum remark wins Rumsfeld an award |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2 December 2003 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2004\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Boris|Johnson}}\n| [[File:Boris Johnson -opening bell at NASDAQ-14Sept2009-3c cropped.jpg|100px|Boris Johnson|alt=Boris Johnson]]\n| During the [[BBC]]'s light-hearted news quiz show ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'', [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician Johnson commented, \"I could not fail to disagree with you less.\"\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-329474/Bumbling-Boris-lands-Foot-Mouth-award.html |title=Bumbling Boris lands Foot in Mouth award |work=[[Daily Mail]] |publisher=[[Daily Mail and General Trust]] |location=London |date=3 December 2004 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2005\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Rhodri|Morgan}}\n| [[File:Rhodri Morgan.jpg|100px|Rhodri Morgan|alt=Rhodri Morgan]]\n| Welsh politician Rhodri Morgan's second award was given for a quote made during a debate on policing; \"The only thing which isn't up for grabs is no change and I think it's fair to say, it's all to play for, except for no change.\"\n| <ref name=\"rhodri\"/>\n|-\n| 2006\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Naomi|Campbell}}\n| [[File:Naomi Campbell Cannes cropped.jpg|100px|Naomi Campbell|alt=Naomi Campbell]]\n| The English [[supermodel]] picked up the award for saying, \"I love England, especially the food. There's nothing I like more than a lovely bowl of pasta.\"\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/2006/12/12/naomis-super-gaffe |title=Naomi's Super Gaffe |last=Jones |first=Dolly |work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications|Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |location=New York |date=12 December 2006 |accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2007\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Steve|McClaren}}\n| [[File:Steve McClaren 2012 1.jpg|100px|Steve McClaren|alt=Steve McClaren]]\n| For describing footballer [[Wayne Rooney]]: \"He is inexperienced, but he's experienced in terms of what he's been through\", when talking to [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] in his role as [[England national football team manager|England manager]].\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2007/12/11/us-english-idUSL117878120071211 |title=George Bush loses close run for 'Foot in Mouth' |last=Majendie |first=Paul |agency=Reuters |date=11 December 2007 |accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2008\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|George W.|Bush}}\n| [[File:George-W-Bush.jpeg|100px|George W. Bush|alt=George W. Bush]]\n| Bush's award was made during his final year in office as [[President of the United States]]. Entitled a \"Lifetime Achievement Award\", it was given for his \"services to gobbledygook\". His gaffes were described as covering a large number of topics, and included comments such as \"I know what I believe. I will continue to articulate what I believe and what I believe&nbsp;\u2013 I believe what I believe is right\", and, \"I hope you leave here and walk out and say, 'what did he say?'\"\n| <ref name=\"past\">{{cite web |url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/awards/foot-in-mouth-award/foot-in-mouth-winners.html |title=Past winners |publisher=Plain English Campaign |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2008-12-09/news/17911550_1_president-bush-watchdog-conferences |title=President Bush's abuse of English language gets Foot in Mouth award |last=Boyle |first=Christina |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |publisher=Daily News, L.P. |location=New York |date=9 December 2008 |accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Peter|Mandelson|alt=Peter Mandelson}}\n| [[File:Lord Mandelson Allan Warren.JPG|100px|Peter Mandelson]]\n| Awarded for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician's remark on the investigation into the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal]]; \"Perhaps we need not more people looking round more corners but the same people looking round more corners more thoroughly to avoid the small things detracting from the big things the Prime Minister is getting right.\"\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8400350.stm |title=Mandelson wins award for political 'gobbledegook' |work=[[BBC News]] |date=8 December 2009 |accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Jamie|Redknapp}}\n| [[File:Redknapp, Jamie (crop).jpg|100px|Jamie Redknapp|alt=Jamie Redknapp]]\n| Repeated misuse of the word \"literally\" made during his career as a sports commentator, in such quotes as: \"These balls now&nbsp;\u2013 they literally explode off your feet.\"\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1337341/Boris-Johnson-Jamie-Redknapp-shamed-poor-use-English.html |title=Boris Johnson and Jamie Redknapp shamed over poor use of English |work=[[Daily Mail]] |publisher=[[Daily Mail and General Trust]] |location=London |date=10 December 2010 |author=Daily Mail Reporter |accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Silvio|Berlusconi}}\n| [[File:Berlusconi-2010-1.jpg|100px|alt=Silvio Berlusconi|Silvio Berlusconi]]\n| The former [[Prime Minister of Italy|Italian Prime Minister]] received the award for comments such as \"I am pretty often faithful\", when talking about fidelity in 2006, and describing [[Barack Obama]] in 2008 as being \"Handsome, young and also suntanned\".\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/topics/weather/8944144/Met-Office-wins-award-for-bad-English-for-using-phrase-a-rash-of-beefy-showers.html |title=Met Office wins award for bad English for using phrase 'a rash of beefy showers' |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] |location=London |last=Bloxham |first=Andy |date=9 December 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corpcommsmagazine.co.uk/news/1971-plain-english-awards |title=Plain English Awards |publisher=CorpComms |last=Humphris |first=Rachel |date=9 December 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Mitt|Romney}}\n| [[File:Mitt Romney.jpg|100px|alt=Mitt Romney|Mitt Romney]]\n| [[2012 U.S. Presidential election|U.S. Presidential candidate]] Mitt Romney received the award for making gaffes on the domestic front: \"I like being able to fire people who provide services to me\"; on the international stage, for example, regarding the [[2012 London Olympics|London Olympics]]: \"There are a few things that were disconcerting. The stories about the private security firm not having enough people, the supposed strike of the immigration and customs officials \u2013 that obviously is not something which is encouraging\"; and generally incomprehensible comments such as \"I believe in an America where millions of Americans believe in an America that's the America millions of Americans believe in. That's the America I love.\"\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=2012 Foot in Mouth award winner|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/awards/foot-in-mouth-award.html|work=Plain English Campaign|accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n| 2013\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Godfrey|Bloom}}\n| [[File:Godfrey Bloom.jpg|100px|alt=Godfrey Bloom|Godfrey Bloom]]\n| [[United Kingdom Independence Party]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] Godfrey Bloom, who sits in the body as an Independent, received the award after making a series of controversial statements in 2013, including describing countries that receive foreign aid from the UK as \"[[Bongo Bongo Land]]\", saying that women don't \"clean behind the fridge enough\", jokingly referring to female members of an audience as \"sluts\" and assaulting one journalist and threatening another. A spokesman called him \"an overwhelming choice\" who \"could easily have won this award on at least two other occasions... [he's] a wince-inducing gaffe machine and we could fill a page or two with his ill-advised quotes from 2013 alone.\"\n| <ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite web|title=Foot in mouth gong for Godfrey Bloom, Yorkshire and Humber MEP|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-25215093|work=BBC News|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"2013 Foot in Mouth award winner\">{{cite web|title=2013 Foot in Mouth award winner|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/campaigning/awards/2013-awards/foot-in-mouth-award.html|work=Plain English Campaign|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|2014\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Russell|Brand}}\n| [[File:Russell Brand Arthur Premier mike.jpg|100px|alt=Russell Brand|Russell Brand]]\n|The Plain English Campaign said that Brand was \"out on his own\" among contenders for the title, adding: \"While we admire Russell's determination to open up a debate about democracy and the dire state of the world, we struggle to make sense of most of his comments.\"\n\nAmong Brand's quotes singled out by the campaign as award-winners were: \"The internal mayhem I'm feeling is spilling out everywhere. I loved it, and felt very connected to activism - particularly activism that feels loaded with potential. Not the oppositional activism that seems like there's a stasis around it - earnestly sincere, but a monolith equal to the establishment.\"\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Russell Brand wins award for making the least sense of all|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/russell-brand-wins-award-for-making-the-least-sense-of-all-9900350.html|work=The Independent|date=3 December 2014|accessdate=31 December 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Donald|Trump}}\n| [[File:Donald Trump August 19, 2015 3 by 2.jpg|100px|alt=Donald Trump|Donald Trump]]\n|Donald Trump was at the time campaigning for the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|Republican nomination]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 US presidential election]]. The Plain English Campaign said that Trump was \"unrivalled\". In particular the campaign cited his remarks on Mexican immigrants: \"They're bringing drugs. They're bringing crime. They're rapists. And some, I assume, are good people.\" It also cited his remarks on [[John McCain]]: \"He\u2019s not a war hero. He was a war hero because he was captured. I like people who weren\u2019t captured.\"\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Foot in Mouth award 2015|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/campaigning/awards/2015-awards/foot-in-mouth-award.html}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Boris|Johnson}}\n| [[File:Boris Johnson -opening bell at NASDAQ-14Sept2009-3c cropped.jpg|100px|Boris Johnson|alt=Boris Johnson]]\n|Boris is regularly a contender for the Foot in Mouth Award and this year proved no exception. This, Boris\u2019s second win, was secured by the unsinkable: \"Brexit means Brexit and we\u2019re going to make a Titanic success of it.\"\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Foot in Mouth award 2016|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/campaigning/awards/2016-awards/foot-in-mouth-award.html}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Jacob|Rees-Mogg}}\n| [[File:Jacobreesmogg.JPG|100px|Jacobreesmogg]]\n|Jacob Rees-Mogg, elbowing aside regular Foot in Mouth favourites Donald Trump and Boris Johnson, described food banks as \"rather uplifting\". Most people consider food banks deeply worrying symptoms of the widening gulf between rich and poor. Rees-Mogg, MP for North East Somerset, seemed to delight in working families relying on charity to survive.\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Foot in Mouth award 2017|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/files/issue88.pdf}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Elon|Musk}}\n| [[File:Elon Musk 2015.jpg|100px|Elon Musk 2015]]\n|Musk made an unexpected entry with the  excruciating comment, \"Sorry pedo guy, you really did ask for it.\u201d as part of a shameful Twitter-rant against Vern Unsworth, who would go on to lead the heroic rescue of [[Tham Luang cave rescue|several stranded Thai children]].\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/files/issue_89.pdf|title=Foot in Mouth award 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Golden Bull Award]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/|Official website of the Plain English Campaign}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foot In Mouth Award}}\n[[Category:Ironic and humorous awards]]\n[[Category:British awards]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1993]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox award\n| name           = Foot in Mouth Award\n| description    = \"a baffling comment by a public figure.\"\n| presenter      = [[Plain English Campaign]]\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| year           = 1993\n| year2          = \n| holder         = [[Elon Musk]] (2018)\n| website        = [http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/campaigning/awards.html plainenglish.co.uk]\n}}\nThe '''Foot in Mouth Award''' is presented each year by the [[Plain English Campaign]] for \"a baffling comment by a public figure\".<ref name=\"thevine\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thevine.com.au/entertainment/top10/top-10-weirdest-awards-ceremonies/ |title=Top 10 weirdest awards ceremonies |work=TheVine.com.au |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] |location=Sydney |date=16 February 2012 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> The award was first made in 1993, when it was given to [[Ted Dexter]], the chairman of selectors for the [[England cricket team]]. It was awarded again the following year, and, after a two-year break, annually from 1997.<ref name=\"past\"/>\n\nThe Plain English Campaign was set up in 1979 when the founder, [[Chrissie Maher]], shredded hundreds of jargon-filled forms and documents in [[Parliament Square]], London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ljmu.ac.uk/Graduation/114808.htm |title=Chrissie Maher |publisher=[[Liverpool John Moores University]] |last=Grant |first=Neil |date=22 September 2010 |accessdate=18 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022175452/http://www.ljmu.ac.uk/Graduation/114808.htm |archivedate=22 October 2012 }}</ref> The group made their first awards the next year, rewarding those organisations that used plain English, and highlighting those that did not.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/awards/about-the-awards.html |title=About the awards |publisher=Plain English Campaign |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> Although the Foot in Mouth award was first made in 1993, a specific acknowledgment was made to a comment by [[Dan Quayle]], [[Vice President of the United States]] in 1991.<ref name=\"past\"/>\n\nThe award has been presented 20 times, and only [[Rhodri Morgan]] and [[Boris Johnson]] have received it more than once. The Welsh politician won in both 1998 and 2005, and made a light-hearted response to his second win, claiming that the first award had \"made [his] name.\"<ref name=\"past\"/> Politicians have been recipients of the award more times than any other group of people, collecting it on 14 occasions; people from the world of sport have won four times. The 43rd President of the United States, [[George W. Bush]], received the award in 2008, with the subtitle \"Lifetime Achievement Award\", given not for a single quote, but for his continued \"services to gobbledygook\".<ref name=\"past\"/>\n\n==Winners==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ Foot in Mouth award winners\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"140px\"| Recipient\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Image\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Rationale\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Ref\n|-\n| 1991\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Dan|Quayle}}\n| [[File:Dan Quayle crop.jpg|100px|Dan Quayle|alt=Dan Quayle]]\n| Although the Foot in Mouth award was not introduced until 1993, the [[Vice President of the United States]], Dan Quayle received a special mention during the 1991 awards for his tent metaphor: \"We offer the party as a big tent. How we do that [recognise the [[big tent]] philosophy] with the platform, the preamble to the platform or whatnot, that remains to be seen. But that message will have to be articulated with great clarity.\"\n| <ref name=\"past\"/>\n|-\n| 1993\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Ted|Dexter}}\n| &ndash;\n| Dexter, a senior figure in the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]], won the inaugural award for trying to explain a loss by the [[England cricket team]] by saying: \"Maybe we are in the wrong sign. Maybe Venus is in the wrong juxtaposition with something else. I don't know.\"\n| <ref name=\"past\"/>\n|-\n| 1994\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Gordon|Brown}}\n| [[File:Gordon Brown smiles.jpg|100px|Gordon Brown|alt=Gordon Brown]]\n| As the [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]], Brown gave a speech on \"New Economics\" full of baffling jargon such as; \"the growth of post neo-classical [[endogenous growth theory]]\" and \"debate over the meaning and implications of competitiveness at the level of individuals, the firm or the nation and the role of government in fashioning modern industrial policies which focus on nurturing competitiveness.\"\n| <ref name=\"past\"/>\n|-\n| 1997\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Nick|Underwood|nolink=1}}\n| &ndash;\n| A member of the ''[[Teletubbies]]'' marketing department, Underwood won the award for his explanation that; \"in life, there are all colours and the Teletubbies are a reflection of that. There are no nationalities in the ''Teletubbies''&nbsp;\u2013 they are techno-babies, but they are supposed to reflect life in that sense.\"\n| <ref name=\"past\"/>\n|-\n| 1998\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Rhodri|Morgan}}\n| [[File:Rhodri Morgan.jpg|100px|Rhodri Morgan|alt=Rhodri Morgan]]\n| Rhodri Morgan, the [[First Minister of Wales]], confused interviewer [[Jeremy Paxman]] when asked if he would like to be leader of the [[National Assembly for Wales|Welsh Assembly]], by responding: \"Does a one-legged duck swim in circles?\"\n| <ref name=\"rhodri\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/4523636.stm |title=Morgan's gobbledegook award No. 2 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=13 December 2005 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>\n \n|-\n| 1999\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Glenn|Hoddle}}\n| [[File:Glenn Hoddle2.jpg|100px|Glenn Hoddle|alt=Glenn Hoddle]]\n| The [[England national football team manager|England football manager]] won the award for his response to a question about his earlier comments that disabled people were born that way because they were being punished for sins in former lives: \"I do not believe that. At this moment in time, if that changes in years to come I don't know, but what happens here today and changes as we go along that is part of life's learning and part of your inner beliefs. But at this moment in time I did not say them things and at the end of the day I want to put that on record because it has hurt people.\"\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/1999/dec/08/5 |title=Prescott's prize for bad language |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |location=London |date=8 December 1999 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2000\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Alicia|Silverstone}}\n| [[File:Alica Silverstone 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg|100px|Alicia Silverstone|alt=Alicia Silverstone]]\n| The American actress, star of ''[[Clueless (film)|Clueless]]'', was awarded for her comment: \"I think that ''Clueless'' was very deep. I think it was deep in the way that it was very light. I think lightness has to come from a very deep place if it's true lightness.\"\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1057660.stm |title=Alicia leaves us Clueless |work=[[BBC News]] |date=6 December 2000 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2001\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Tracey|Emin}}\n| [[File:Tracey Emin 1-cropped.jpg|100px|Tracey Emin|alt=Tracey Emin]]\n| Artist Tracey Emin won the award for her comment: \"When it comes to words I have a uniqueness that I find almost impossible in terms of art&nbsp;\u2013 and it's my words that actually make my art quite unique.\"\n| <ref name=\"gere\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/dec/05/film.filmnews |title=Gere stumbles across award |last=Ezard |first=John |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |location=London |date=5 December 2002 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| 2002\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Richard|Gere}}\n| [[File:Richardgere.jpg|100px|Richard Gere|alt=Richard Gere]]\n| The American actor was presented with the award for his philosophical comment: \"I know who I am. No one else knows who I am. If I was a giraffe and somebody said I was a snake, I'd think 'No, actually I am a giraffe.\"\n| <ref name=\"gere\"/>\n|-\n| 2003\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Donald|Rumsfeld}}\n| [[File:Donald Rumsfeld Defenselink.jpg|100px|Donald Rumsfeld|alt=Donald Rumsfeld]]\n| For his overuse of the word \"know\" during a press briefing given as [[United States Secretary of Defense]]: \"Reports that say that something hasn't happened are always interesting to me, because as we know, [[there are known knowns]]; there are things we know we know. We also know there are known unknowns; that is to say we know there are some things we do not know. But there are also unknown unknowns&nbsp;\u2014 the ones we don't know we don't know.\"\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/3254852.stm |title=Rum remark wins Rumsfeld an award |work=[[BBC News]] |date=2 December 2003 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2004\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Boris|Johnson}}\n| [[File:Boris Johnson -opening bell at NASDAQ-14Sept2009-3c cropped.jpg|100px|Boris Johnson|alt=Boris Johnson]]\n| During the [[BBC]]'s light-hearted news quiz show ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'', [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician Johnson commented, \"I could not fail to disagree with you less.\"\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-329474/Bumbling-Boris-lands-Foot-Mouth-award.html |title=Bumbling Boris lands Foot in Mouth award |work=[[Daily Mail]] |publisher=[[Daily Mail and General Trust]] |location=London |date=3 December 2004 |accessdate=30 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2005\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Rhodri|Morgan}}\n| [[File:Rhodri Morgan.jpg|100px|Rhodri Morgan|alt=Rhodri Morgan]]\n| Welsh politician Rhodri Morgan's second award was given for a quote made during a debate on policing; \"The only thing which isn't up for grabs is no change and I think it's fair to say, it's all to play for, except for no change.\"\n| <ref name=\"rhodri\"/>\n|-\n| 2006\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Naomi|Campbell}}\n| [[File:Naomi Campbell Cannes cropped.jpg|100px|Naomi Campbell|alt=Naomi Campbell]]\n| The English [[supermodel]] picked up the award for saying, \"I love England, especially the food. There's nothing I like more than a lovely bowl of pasta.\"\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/2006/12/12/naomis-super-gaffe |title=Naomi's Super Gaffe |last=Jones |first=Dolly |work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications|Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |location=New York |date=12 December 2006 |accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2007\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Steve|McClaren}}\n| [[File:Steve McClaren 2012 1.jpg|100px|Steve McClaren|alt=Steve McClaren]]\n| For describing footballer [[Wayne Rooney]]: \"He is inexperienced, but he's experienced in terms of what he's been through\", when talking to [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] in his role as [[England national football team manager|England manager]].\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2007/12/11/us-english-idUSL117878120071211 |title=George Bush loses close run for 'Foot in Mouth' |last=Majendie |first=Paul |agency=Reuters |date=11 December 2007 |accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2008\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|George W.|Bush}}\n| [[File:George-W-Bush.jpeg|100px|George W. Bush|alt=George W. Bush]]\n| Bush's award was made during his final year in office as [[President of the United States]]. Entitled a \"Lifetime Achievement Award\", it was given for his \"services to gobbledygook\". His gaffes were described as covering a large number of topics, and included comments such as \"I know what I believe. I will continue to articulate what I believe and what I believe&nbsp;\u2013 I believe what I believe is right\", and, \"I hope you leave here and walk out and say, 'what did he say?'\"\n| <ref name=\"past\">{{cite web |url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/awards/foot-in-mouth-award/foot-in-mouth-winners.html |title=Past winners |publisher=Plain English Campaign |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2008-12-09/news/17911550_1_president-bush-watchdog-conferences |title=President Bush's abuse of English language gets Foot in Mouth award |last=Boyle |first=Christina |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |publisher=Daily News, L.P. |location=New York |date=9 December 2008 |accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Peter|Mandelson|alt=Peter Mandelson}}\n| [[File:Lord Mandelson Allan Warren.JPG|100px|Peter Mandelson]]\n| Awarded for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician's remark on the investigation into the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal]]; \"Perhaps we need not more people looking round more corners but the same people looking round more corners more thoroughly to avoid the small things detracting from the big things the Prime Minister is getting right.\"\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8400350.stm |title=Mandelson wins award for political 'gobbledegook' |work=[[BBC News]] |date=8 December 2009 |accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Jamie|Redknapp}}\n| [[File:Redknapp, Jamie (crop).jpg|100px|Jamie Redknapp|alt=Jamie Redknapp]]\n| Repeated misuse of the word \"literally\" made during his career as a sports commentator, in such quotes as: \"These balls now&nbsp;\u2013 they literally explode off your feet.\"\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1337341/Boris-Johnson-Jamie-Redknapp-shamed-poor-use-English.html |title=Boris Johnson and Jamie Redknapp shamed over poor use of English |work=[[Daily Mail]] |publisher=[[Daily Mail and General Trust]] |location=London |date=10 December 2010 |author=Daily Mail Reporter |accessdate=28 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Silvio|Berlusconi}}\n| [[File:Berlusconi-2010-1.jpg|100px|alt=Silvio Berlusconi|Silvio Berlusconi]]\n| The former [[Prime Minister of Italy|Italian Prime Minister]] received the award for comments such as \"I am pretty often faithful\", when talking about fidelity in 2006, and describing [[Barack Obama]] in 2008 as being \"Handsome, young and also suntanned\".\n| <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/topics/weather/8944144/Met-Office-wins-award-for-bad-English-for-using-phrase-a-rash-of-beefy-showers.html |title=Met Office wins award for bad English for using phrase 'a rash of beefy showers' |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] |location=London |last=Bloxham |first=Andy |date=9 December 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corpcommsmagazine.co.uk/news/1971-plain-english-awards |title=Plain English Awards |publisher=CorpComms |last=Humphris |first=Rachel |date=9 December 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Mitt|Romney}}\n| [[File:Mitt Romney.jpg|100px|alt=Mitt Romney|Mitt Romney]]\n| [[2012 U.S. Presidential election|U.S. Presidential candidate]] Mitt Romney received the award for making gaffes on the domestic front: \"I like being able to fire people who provide services to me\"; on the international stage, for example, regarding the [[2012 London Olympics|London Olympics]]: \"There are a few things that were disconcerting. The stories about the private security firm not having enough people, the supposed strike of the immigration and customs officials \u2013 that obviously is not something which is encouraging\"; and generally incomprehensible comments such as \"I believe in an America where millions of Americans believe in an America that's the America millions of Americans believe in. That's the America I love.\"\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=2012 Foot in Mouth award winner|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/awards/foot-in-mouth-award.html|work=Plain English Campaign|accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n| 2013\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Godfrey|Bloom}}\n| [[File:Godfrey Bloom.jpg|100px|alt=Godfrey Bloom|Godfrey Bloom]]\n| [[United Kingdom Independence Party]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] Godfrey Bloom, who sits in the body as an Independent, received the award after making a series of controversial statements in 2013, including describing countries that receive foreign aid from the UK as \"[[Bongo Bongo Land]]\", saying that women don't \"clean behind the fridge enough\", jokingly referring to female members of an audience as \"sluts\" and assaulting one journalist and threatening another. A spokesman called him \"an overwhelming choice\" who \"could easily have won this award on at least two other occasions... [he's] a wince-inducing gaffe machine and we could fill a page or two with his ill-advised quotes from 2013 alone.\"\n| <ref name=\"BBC News\">{{cite web|title=Foot in mouth gong for Godfrey Bloom, Yorkshire and Humber MEP|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-25215093|work=BBC News|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"2013 Foot in Mouth award winner\">{{cite web|title=2013 Foot in Mouth award winner|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/campaigning/awards/2013-awards/foot-in-mouth-award.html|work=Plain English Campaign|accessdate=6 December 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|2014\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Russell|Brand}}\n| [[File:Russell Brand Arthur Premier mike.jpg|100px|alt=Russell Brand|Russell Brand]]\n|The Plain English Campaign said that Brand was \"out on his own\" among contenders for the title, adding: \"While we admire Russell's determination to open up a debate about democracy and the dire state of the world, we struggle to make sense of most of his comments.\"\n\nAmong Brand's quotes singled out by the campaign as award-winners were: \"The internal mayhem I'm feeling is spilling out everywhere. I loved it, and felt very connected to activism - particularly activism that feels loaded with potential. Not the oppositional activism that seems like there's a stasis around it - earnestly sincere, but a monolith equal to the establishment.\"\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Russell Brand wins award for making the least sense of all|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/russell-brand-wins-award-for-making-the-least-sense-of-all-9900350.html|work=The Independent|date=3 December 2014|accessdate=31 December 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|2015\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Donald|Trump}}\n| [[File:Donald Trump August 19, 2015 3 by 2.jpg|100px|alt=Donald Trump|Donald Trump]]\n|Donald Trump was at the time campaigning for the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|Republican nomination]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 US presidential election]]. The Plain English Campaign said that Trump was \"unrivalled\". In particular the campaign cited his remarks on Mexican immigrants: \"They're bringing drugs. They're bringing crime. They're rapists. And some, I assume, are good people.\" It also cited his remarks on [[John McCain]]: \"He\u2019s not a war hero. He was a war hero because he was captured. I like people who weren\u2019t captured.\"\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Foot in Mouth award 2015|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/campaigning/awards/2015-awards/foot-in-mouth-award.html}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Boris|Johnson}}\n| [[File:Boris Johnson -opening bell at NASDAQ-14Sept2009-3c cropped.jpg|100px|Boris Johnson|alt=Boris Johnson]]\n|Boris is regularly a contender for the Foot in Mouth Award and this year proved no exception. This, Boris\u2019s second win, was secured by the unsinkable: \"Brexit means Brexit and we\u2019re going to make a Titanic success of it.\"\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Foot in Mouth award 2016|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/campaigning/awards/2016-awards/foot-in-mouth-award.html}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Jacob|Rees-Mogg}}\n| [[File:Jacobreesmogg.JPG|100px|Jacobreesmogg]]\n|Jacob Rees-Mogg, elbowing aside regular Foot in Mouth favourites Donald Trump and Boris Johnson, described food banks as \"rather uplifting\". Most people consider food banks deeply worrying symptoms of the widening gulf between rich and poor. Rees-Mogg, MP for North East Somerset, seemed to delight in working families relying on charity to survive.\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Foot in Mouth award 2017|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/files/issue88.pdf}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n! scope=\"row\" | {{sortname|Elon|Musk}}\n| [[File:Elon Musk 2015.jpg|100px|Elon Musk 2015]]\n|Musk made an unexpected entry with the  excruciating comment, \"Sorry pedo guy, you really did ask for it.\u201d as part of a shameful Twitter-rant against Vern Unsworth, who would go on to lead the heroic rescue of [[Tham Luang cave rescue|several stranded Thai children]].\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/files/issue_89.pdf|title=Foot in Mouth award 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Golden Bull Award]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.plainenglish.co.uk/|Official website of the Plain English Campaign}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foot In Mouth Award}}\n[[Category:Ironic and humorous awards]]\n[[Category:British awards]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1993]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c4:222f:d600:2c6b:415f:8637:ed1b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foot_in_Mouth_Award"}
